2026-04-21 01:35:43 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module control electronics / light-sensor comparator network'] hypothesis_explanation='The power module is stable and continuously providing ~12 V, as confirmed by the green LED and voltage tests. The control module’s relay contacts deliver a steady ~11.8 V to the load without any drop during the observed 0.5 s outages, ruling out the relay coil, contacts, and light‑dependent switching as the cause of the periodic lamp interruptions. The load module has correct polarity (diode forward‑biased at ~0.77 V) and both the main lamp and indicator branch test as good hardware with nominal resistance, so the load itself is not intermittently open or shorted. \n\nDespite this, the overall circuit is reported as non‑convergent/oscillating, and the lamp exhibits periodic brief dropouts that do *not* correspond to supply interruptions or relay operation. The only remaining plausible root cause is an internal instability in the ambient sensor module’s control electronics (the light sensor–comparator/driver network) that is not fully captured at the relay contacts but perturbs the circuit enough to drive the simulator into an oscillatory state and manifest as brief lamp off events. That network is the only active control element left that could create regular ~20 s transients without changing the measured DC at the switched output.\n\nTherefore the fault is localized to the ambient sensor module’s internal control electronics / light‑sensor comparator network, which should be repaired or replaced as a unit.'
